The text of this edition, though it departs from that of Halm* in more than fifty places, is conservative, for in eighteen instances Ι return to the Mss„ while in the others my readings are either not without some MS. authority, or else the correction is of the simplest description possible and i111peratively demanded by the context or by Tacitean usage, as will be evident even from the necessarily brief discussion in the Critical Appendix.

Special pains have been bestowed upon the prosody of the proper names, so far as this may be determined by their occurrence in poetry and ‘the‘ Greek transliterations, conflicting though their evidence often is. The linguistic criteria so constantly employed I have found quite unreliable, partly because of the doubtful etymology of the names themselves, partly because they have passed through a process of Latinization with all the prosodical changes which that involved.

The innovation of superimposing· the modern upon the ancient map, designed to obviate the frequent necessity or expediency of consulting two maps, will, I hope, commend itself to teachers and students alike.
